WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.320
Ever wondered what these little badges mean? Stable is the default. No badge at all,

00:00:04.320 --> 00:00:08.720
it's probably stable. This function is not going to have a breaking change without a

00:00:08.720 --> 00:00:14.000
formal deprecation cycle. Experimental means breaking changes could happen with no warning,

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:18.080
so try this function out, give feedback to the devs, but don't build anything critical with it.

00:00:18.719 --> 00:00:22.879
Deprecated means there's a better alternative to this function and it's on its way out.

00:00:22.879 --> 00:00:27.840
You'll get a warning telling you exactly what to use instead. Eventually it becomes defunct,

00:00:27.840 --> 00:00:32.720
throwing an error, or is simply deleted. Superseded is an interesting one. There's a

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:37.360
better alternative, but the function's not going away. It won't warn you and it's actually safe

00:00:37.360 --> 00:00:42.320
to use. The docs will just quietly point you to the better, newer function. Curious about

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:46.799
a function's lifecycle status? Type the function like this and the badge is right at the top.

